post_text:
The Texas Art Education Association (TAEA) announced GISD as a winner of the organization's 2020 District of Distinction Award. GISD received the honor for its outstanding leadership in promoting the arts in the school district and the wider community.

More than 1,000 districts were eligible to apply for the TAEA Visual Arts Award, and only 42 received the distinction. Each district met the documented standards of a 12-point rubric that examined the district’s visual art program from participation in TAEA through membership, exhibitions and contents, as well as community engagement in the visual arts through field experiences, community service, and collaboration.

Congratulations to the dedicated teachers and staff members whose work brought this recognition to GISD!

Technology Update:

For students who have elected to return for in-person learning beginning on Sept. 10, we ask that those who are able to bring their own device (BYOD) to and school daily do so, for this semester only, as we wait for our new order of devices to arrive.

We understand that this is not an option for everyone, but for those who are able, doing so will allow us to meet the needs of our students without access to their own devices.

If your student can bring a personal device (not one borrowed from GISD) for learning this semester, we ask that you please fill out the form at the link below. This will allow us to gather a count of how many students will bring their own devices.

NOTE: We do not recommend bringing a personal iPad as your device.

City of Georgetown, Texas - Government
August 31 at 3:00 PM ·

As students are starting the new school year, please join us for a new edition of Tuesday Talks with Britin and Ann as we focus on schools in Georgetown at noon Tuesday, Sept. 1. Schools play an important role in our community and our history! Britin and Ann will take a look back at Georgetown's historic school buildings and some stories that may surprise you, where students from the youngest learners to college grads spent time in first-rate classrooms as well as "chicken coops!” Visit historic.georgetown.org for more information!

post_text: Earlier this month, the Georgetown ISD Education Foundation awarded more than $38,000 in collaborative learning grants to teachers in GISD! ICYMI, they have been sharing information about each of these grants on their Facebook page. Follow along to see the creative projects and opportunities available to GISD students, thanks to the support of our Education Foundation and generous donors around the community.
shared_text:
Georgetown ISD Education Foundation
August 28 at 6:00 PM ·

We remain in the STEM field for our next grant, with our recipients teaming up across 2 middle school campsuses to bring neuroscience exploration to our students. With this grant, students will get to experience relevant real world learning opportunities through the "concussion lab," including the mechanics of brain injuries and how to prevent them.

The Neuroscience Brain Project
Submitted by Terri Henry of Benold Middle School and Maria Mesa of James Tippit Middle
This grant will receive $3405.70

post_text: Have you filled out your Census? Be counted and help our community receive important funding for programs like school lunch!
shared_text:
City of Georgetown, Texas - Government
July 8 at 4:00 PM ·

☘️ Did you know Ireland has the fastest population growth?

Thank you, students, parents and staff, for sharing your feedback in our recent survey. More than 8,000 of you participated, and those results are now being used to inform planning for a return to school in August.

While plans are subject to change as local and state leaders respond to the needs of our community, at this time, GISD is planning an option for families to choose the learning environment that fits their needs:
➡️ In-person where a student attends classes at their home campus with physical distancing and other safety measures in place OR
➡️ Full-time GISD virtual instruction from home

View the survey results and read more about plans for the 2020-21 school year here: https://bit.ly/2Z9t9OU

post_text:
Eastview Highschool senior Jebron Perkins gave a moving speech at last night's graduation ceremony that's fitting for every graduate, no matter where you are. Here's an excerpt:
"Make it the beginning of a journey that makes this place better than you found it. Just by being here, each and every one of you defied the odds... not that I expected any less! For this entire school year, you have proven yourself as a true Patriot, one who perseveres in the face of adversity. For you are not only graduating but you are elevating this world to the best it's ever been, and that is a class of 2020 legacy that corona cannot destroy."

Watch the entire live feed at https://youtu.be/P1eWUF_GUZw.

Jebron, you make us #GISDProud and wish you and your peers the best as you enter the next phase of your life. You are prepared to make the change you want to see!

May 27 at 11:09 AM · Georgetown, TX ·

During the May board meeting, which was held virtually Monday, May 18, the GISD board of trustees recognized Jack Frost Citizens of the Month from Georgetown and East View High Schools. Named in honor of former superintendent Jack Frost, the award is presented to deserving high school seniors who demonstrate outstanding citizenship in and outside of school.

Congratulations to the following students: Christopher Milton and Lilian Rembert from East View High School (April), Gina Hernandez and Jaylyn Gamez from East View High School (May), Jack Bartholomew, from Georgetown High School (April) and Caroline Skeels and Channing McGee from Georgetown High School (May).

During the May board meeting, which was held virtually Monday, May 18, the GISD board of trustees recognized Jack Frost Citizens of the Month from Georgetown and East View High Schools. Named in honor of former superintendent Jack Frost, the award is presented to deserving high school seniors who demonstrate outstanding citizenship in and outside of school.

Congratulations to the following students: Christopher Milton and Lilian Rembert from East View High School (April), Gina Hernandez and Jaylyn Gamez from East View High School (May), Jack Bartholomew, from Georgetown High School (April) and Caroline Skeels and Channing McGee from Georgetown High School (May).

post_text: We are incredibly proud of the 13 students from Douglas Benold Middle School, Georgetown High School, and East View High School who were recognized in the Congressional Art Competition! The arts are alive and thriving in Georgetown, TX. Thank you to the educators who inspire creativity and support opportunities like this for recognition. We are #GISDProud!
shared_text:
U.S. Representative John Carter added 20 new photos to the album: 2020 Congressional Art Competition Winners.
May 20 at 12:41 PM ·

I am proud to announce the 2020 TX-31 Congressional Art Competition Winners. While we couldn’t do our normal celebration and awards ceremony, I want every participant to know how proud I am of them. Sixty-six students participated, and each piece of artwork represented the immense talent present in TX-31.

Our Overall Best In Show Winner is Axel Hernandez from Belton New Tech High School. Axel will receive complimentary airfare from Southwest Airlines to visit Washington, DC and see his artwork hung in the United States Capitol.

Please join me in congratulating all of our participants!

The arts are alive and thriving in Georgetown, TX. Thank you to the educators who inspire creativity and support opportunities like this for recognition. We are #GISDProud!

post_text:
Earlier today, Dr. Brent sent a voice message to GISD families sharing an important update. Governor Abbott issued an executive order today that closed all public schools through the end of the school year. We will continue to deliver learning through remote online instruction while keeping district facilities closed through May 28.

We know that you have questions, and we are working diligently on plans for end-of-year events and activities, including graduation, as well as plans for extra-curricular activities, and retrieving items currently at campuses.

We will keep you informed as more information becomes available in the coming days.

post_text:
"The school librarians in Georgetown ISD, Texas, have been hard at work these weeks supporting our students and our staff in every way we can. As central figures in a school building who work with multiple departments, school librarians are in a unique position to help many faculty with the tools and resources they need to get their students learning and engaging in these difficult times."

April is #NationalSchoolLibraryMonth, and in this article for the American Association of School Librarians, East View High School Librarian Deah Hester sheds light on the work she and her colleagues have been doing during this period of distance learning. Please join us in saying thank you to our librarians for their invaluable contributions to our students.
